  "body": "This PR introduces that concept of a \"thread aware LB\". A thread aware\r\nLB is global to a cluster. Each worker creates its local LB via a factory\r\nfunction on host set updates. This new pattern has been used in the ring\r\nhash LB such that ring calculations only take place on the main thread, since\r\nwith large ring sizes they can be extremely costly. Other LBs would benefit\r\nfrom conversion in the future but that has not been done with this change.\r\n\r\nOne particular note about the ring hash LB change: We now only compute global\r\npanic at host set update time. This reduces the number of rings that require\r\ncomputation to one per update. This is a reasonable compromise as the runtime\r\nhealthy panic setting will rarely if ever change.\r\n\r\nAs part of this change, the subset LB has been modified slightly to streamline\r\nthe LB creation/update logic. In this change, the subset LB still uses a per\r\nworker ring hash LB. In a future change, when the subset LB is converted to\r\nthread aware, it can properly use a thread aware ring hash LB also.\r\n\r\nNote that this change also substantially cleans up the init logic inside the\r\ncluster manager to reduce duplicate load balancer creates, posts to threads\r\nbefore init is complete, etc. I have tried to comment things very well but\r\nlet me know if more comments are needed.\r\n\r\n*Risk Level*: Medium/High. Tricky/core code.\r\n\r\n*Testing*: Unit only for main change. Integration covers the major cluster manager\r\nchanges. Note that the header integration test was relying on broken behavior\r\n(EDS cluster would have no healthy hosts and fail, and then succeed on the \r\nnext iteration) so I had to fix the test after I streamlined the cluster manager code.\r\n\r\n*Docs Changes*: N/A\r\n\r\n*Release Notes*: N/A\r\n\r\nFixes https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/issues/1941\r\n",
